    <paragraphs>
      <title>Division</title>
      <p>
        Fractions can perhaps best be understood with division, where the numerator is divided into
        the denominator number of equal parts. The size of one of those parts is the value of the
        fraction.
      </p>

      <p>
        For example, we can view the fraction <m>\frac{3}{7}</m> as <m>3</m> divided into <m>7</m>
        equal parts, as in <xref ref="figure-fraction-division"/>. Just one of those parts
        represents <m>\frac{3}{7}</m>.
      </p>

      <figure xml:id="figure-fraction-division">
        <caption>Representing <m>\frac{3}{7}</m> on a number line.</caption>
        <image width="67%">
          <shortdescription>
            a number line with a ruler superimposed over the segment from 0 to 3; the ruler is
            subdivided into seven pieces; an arrow points down from the first ruler tick to a point
            on the number line that is marked 3/7
          </shortdescription>
          <latex-image label="fraction-division">
            \begin{tikzpicture}
              \begin{axis}[
                  numberline,
                  xmin=-1,
                  xmax=4,
                  xtick={-1,0,3,4},
                  minor xtick={{}},
                  extra x ticks={0.42},
                  extra x tick labels={\(\frac{3}{7}\)},
                  xlabel={},
                  width=0.47\orccaprintwidth
                ]
                \addplot[guideline] coordinates {(0,0) (0,0.5) (3,0.5) (3,0)};
                \addplot[guideline,&lt;-] coordinates {(0.428571,0) (0.428571,0.5)} node[above] {\(3\) divided by \(7\)};
                \addplot[guideline] coordinates {(0.857142,0.4) (0.857142,0.5)};
                \addplot[guideline] coordinates {(1.285714,0.4) (1.285714,0.5)};
                \addplot[guideline] coordinates {(1.71428,0.4) (1.71428,0.5)};
                \addplot[guideline] coordinates {(2.142857,0.4) (2.1428575,0.5)};
                \addplot[guideline] coordinates {(2.571428,0.4) (2.5714282,0.5)};
              \end{axis}
            \end{tikzpicture}
          </latex-image>
        </image>
      </figure>

      <exercise>
        <title>Seeing a Fraction as Division Arithmetic</title>
        <webwork>
          <statement>
            <p>
              The fraction <m>\frac{21}{40}</m> can be thought of as dividing the whole number
              <var name="21" width="5" /> into <var name="40" width="5" /> equal-sized parts.
            </p>
          </statement>
          <solution>
            <p>
              Since <m>\frac{21}{40}</m> means the same as <m>21\div40</m>, it can be thought of as
              dividing <m>21</m> into <m>40</m> equal parts.
            </p>
          </solution>
        </webwork>
      </exercise>
    </paragraphs>
  </subsection> -->

  <subsection>
    <title>Equivalent Fractions</title>
    <p>
      Two different-looking fractions can represent the same amount. Consider <m>\frac{2}{5}</m> and
      <m>\frac{6}{15}</m> represented in various ways in
      <xref first="figure-equivalent-fractions-parts" last="figure-equivalent-fractions-division"/>.
    </p>

    <sidebyside widths="32% 32% 32%" margins="0%" valign="bottom">
      <figure xml:id="figure-equivalent-fractions-parts">
        <caption><m>\frac{2}{5}</m> and <m>\frac{6}{15}</m> as equal parts of a whole</caption>
        <image>
          <shortdescription>
            one rectangle that is five times as wide as it is tall; the entire rectangle is shaded;
            there is a 1 in the center of the rectangle; a second rectangle that is also five times
            as wide as it is tall; it is subdivided equally into five squares; the first two squares
            are shaded; there is a 1/5 in the center of each of the first two squares; a third
            rectangle that is also five times as wide as it is tall; it is subdivided equally into
            fifteen adjacent rectangles; the first six of these smaller rectangles are shaded; there
            is a 1/15 in the center of each of the first six smaller rectangles
          </shortdescription>
          <latex-image label="equivalent-fractions-parts">
            \begin{tikzpicture}
              \draw (0,0) rectangle (5,1);
              \draw[fill=firstcolor!20] (0,0) rectangle (2,1);
              \draw (1,0)--(1,1);
              \draw (2,0)--(2,1);
              \draw (3,0)--(3,1);
              \draw (4,0)--(4,1);
              \node at (0.5,0.5) {$\frac{1}{5}$};
              \node at (1.5,0.5) {$\frac{1}{5}$};
              \draw (0,-1.5) rectangle (5,-0.5);
              \draw[fill=firstcolor!20] (0,-1.5) rectangle (2,-0.5);
              \draw (0.3333,-1.5)--(0.3333,-0.5);
              \draw (0.6667,-1.5)--(0.6667,-0.5);
              \draw (1,-1.5)--(1,-0.5);
              \draw (1.3333,-1.5)--(1.3333,-0.5);
              \draw (1.6667,-1.5)--(1.6667,-0.5);
              \draw (2,-1.5)--(2,-0.5);
              \draw (2.3333,-1.5)--(2.3333,-0.5);
              \draw (2.6667,-1.5)--(2.6667,-0.5);
              \draw (3,-1.5)--(3,-0.5);
              \draw (3.3333,-1.5)--(3.3333,-0.5);
              \draw (3.6667,-1.5)--(3.6667,-0.5);
              \draw (4,-1.5)--(4,-0.5);
              \draw (4.3333,-1.5)--(4.3333,-0.5);
              \draw (4.6667,-1.5)--(4.6667,-0.5);
              \node at (0.1667,-1) {$\frac{1}{15}$};
              \node at (0.5,-1) {$\frac{1}{15}$};
              \node at (0.8333,-1) {$\frac{1}{15}$};
              \node at (1.1667,-1) {$\frac{1}{15}$};
              \node at (1.5,-1) {$\frac{1}{15}$};
              \node at (1.8333,-1) {$\frac{1}{15}$};
            \end{tikzpicture}
          </latex-image>
        </image>
      </figure>

      <figure xml:id="figure-equivalent-fractions-number-line">
        <caption><m>\frac{2}{5}</m>, <m>\frac{6}{15}</m> as equal on a number line</caption>
        <image>
          <shortdescription>
            a number line with a curved arrow emanating from 0 and landing to the right at 1/5, then
            again from 1/5 to 2/5; there is a number line with a curved arrow emanating from 0 and
            landing to the right at 1/15, then again from 1/15 to 2/15, then again from 2/15 to
            3/15, then again from 3/15 to 4/15, then again from 4/15 to 5/15, and then again from
            5/15 to 6/15
          </shortdescription>
          <latex-image label="equivalent-fractions-number-line">
            \begin{tikzpicture}
              \begin{axis}[
                  numberline,
                  xmin=0,
                  xmax=1,
                  xtick={0,1},
                  minor xtick={-1,-0.8,...,1},
                  extra x ticks={0.4},
                  extra x tick labels={$\frac{2}{5}$},
                  xlabel={},
                  width=0.32\orccaprintwidth
                ]
                \addplot[firstcurve, -, smooth] coordinates {(0,0) (0.1,0.25) (0.2,0)};
                \addplot[firstcurve, ->, smooth] coordinates {(0.2,0) (0.3,0.25) (0.4,0)};
              \end{axis}
              \begin{axis}[
                  numberline,
                  at={(0,-1cm)},
                  xmin=0,
                  xmax=1,
                  xtick={0,1},
                  minor xtick={-1,-0.8,...,1},
                  extra x ticks={0.4},
                  extra x tick labels={$\frac{6}{15}$},
                  xlabel={},
                  width=0.32\orccaprintwidth
                ]
                \addplot[firstcurve, -, smooth] coordinates {(0,0) (0.0333333,0.25) (0.0666667,0)};
                \addplot[firstcurve, -, smooth] coordinates {(0.0666666,0) (0.1,0.25) (0.1333333,0)};
                \addplot[firstcurve, -, smooth] coordinates {(0.1333333,0) (0.1666667,0.25) (0.2,0)};
                \addplot[firstcurve, -, smooth] coordinates {(0.2,0) (0.2333333,0.25) (0.2666667,0)};
                \addplot[firstcurve, -, smooth] coordinates {(0.2666666,0) (0.3,0.25) (0.3333333,0)};
                \addplot[firstcurve,->, smooth] coordinates {(0.3333333,0) (0.3666667,0.25) (0.4,0)};
              \end{axis}
            \end{tikzpicture}
          </latex-image>
        </image>
      </figure>

      <figure xml:id="figure-equivalent-fractions-division">
        <caption><m>\frac{2}{5}</m> and <m>\frac{6}{15}</m> as equal quotients</caption>
        <image>
          <shortdescription>
            a number line with a ruler superimposed over the segment from 0 to 2; the ruler is
            subdivided into five pieces; an arrow points down from the first ruler tick to a point
            on the number line that is marked 2/5; there is a second number line with a ruler
            superimposed over the segment from 0 to 6; the ruler is subdivided into fifteen pieces;
            an arrow points down from the first ruler tick to a point on the number line that is
            marked 6/15
          </shortdescription>
          <latex-image label="equivalent-fractions-division">
            \begin{tikzpicture}
              \begin{axis}[
                  numberline,
                  xmin=0,
                  xmax=6,
                  xtick={0,1,...,6},
                  minor xtick={{}},
                  extra x ticks={0.4},
                  extra x tick labels={$\frac{2}{5}$},
                  xlabel={},
                  x=0.8cm,
                  width=0.32\orccaprintwidth
                ]
                \addplot[guideline] coordinates {(0,0) (0,1) (2,1) (2,0)};
                \addplot[guideline,&lt;-] coordinates {(0.4,0) (0.4,1)} node[above right] {\(2\) divided by \(5\)};
                \addplot[guideline] coordinates {(0.8,0.8) (0.8,1)};
                \addplot[guideline] coordinates {(1.2,0.8) (1.2,1)};
                \addplot[guideline] coordinates {(1.6,0.8) (1.6,1)};
              \end{axis}
              \begin{axis}[
                  numberline,
                  at={(0,-2cm)},
                  xmin=0,
                  xmax=6,
                  xtick={0,1,...,6},
                  minor xtick={{}},
                  extra x ticks={0.4},
                  extra x tick labels={$\frac{6}{15}$},
                  xlabel={},
                  x=0.8cm,
                  width=0.32\orccaprintwidth
                ]
                \addplot[guideline] coordinates {(0,0) (0,1) (6,1) (6,0)};
                \addplot[guideline,&lt;-] coordinates {(0.4,0) (0.4,1)} node[above right] {\(6\) divided by \(15\)};
                \addplot[guideline] coordinates {(0.8,0.8) (0.8,1)};
                \addplot[guideline] coordinates {(1.2,0.8) (1.2,1)};
                \addplot[guideline] coordinates {(1.6,0.8) (1.6,1)};
                \addplot[guideline] coordinates {(2,0.8) (2,1)};
                \addplot[guideline] coordinates {(2.4,0.8) (2.4,1)};
                \addplot[guideline] coordinates {(2.8,0.8) (2.8,1)};
                \addplot[guideline] coordinates {(3.2,0.8) (3.2,1)};
                \addplot[guideline] coordinates {(3.6,0.8) (3.6,1)};
                \addplot[guideline] coordinates {(4,0.8) (4,1)};
                \addplot[guideline] coordinates {(4.4,0.8) (4.4,1)};
                \addplot[guideline] coordinates {(4.8,0.8) (4.8,1)};
                \addplot[guideline] coordinates {(5.2,0.8) (5.2,1)};
                \addplot[guideline] coordinates {(5.6,0.8) (5.6,1)};
              \end{axis}
            \end{tikzpicture}
          </latex-image>
        </image>
      </figure>
    </sidebyside>
    <p>
      The two fractions <m>\frac{2}{5}</m> and <m>\frac{6}{15}</m> are equal, as these figures show.
      Both fractions are equal to <m>0.4</m> as a decimal. If we must work with this number as a
      fraction, the version that uses smaller numbers, <m>\frac{2}{5}</m>, is preferable. Working
      with smaller numbers decreases the likelihood of making a human error.
    </p>

    <sidebyside widths="68% 29%" margins="0%">
      <p>
        So if you have a fraction like <m>\frac{6}{15}</m>, it's important to try to                          <idx><h>Fraction</h><h>reducing</h></idx>
        <term>reduce</term> it to <q>lowest terms</q>. The most important skill you can have to help          <idx><h>Reduced fraction</h></idx>
        you do this is to know the multiplication table well. If you know it well, you know that
        <m>6=2\cdot3</m> and <m>15=3\cdot5</m>, so you can break down the numerator and denominator           <idx><h>Reducing a fraction</h></idx>
        that way. Both the numerator and denominator are divisible by <m>3</m>, so these <m>3</m>s
        can cancel out.
      </p>
      <p>
        <md>
          <mrow>\frac{6}{15}\amp=\frac{2\cdot3}{3\cdot5}</mrow>
          <mrow>\amp=\frac{2\cdot\cancelhighlight{3}}{\cancelhighlight{3}\cdot5}</mrow>
          <mrow>\amp=\frac{2\cdot1}{1\cdot5}</mrow>
          <mrow>\amp=\frac{2}{5}</mrow>
        </md>
      </p>
    </sidebyside>

    <exercise>
      <title>Reducing Fractions</title>
      <webwork>
        <pg-code>
          Context("LimitedFraction")->flags->set(
              allowMixedNumbers => 0,
              reduceConstants => 1,
              showMixedNumbers => 0
          );
          Parser::Number::NoDecimals;
          @f=(
            Fraction(1, 3)->cmp(studentsMustReduceFractions => 1),
            Fraction(4, 15)->cmp(studentsMustReduceFractions => 1),
            Fraction(7, 9)->cmp(studentsMustReduceFractions => 1)
          );
        </pg-code>
        <introduction>
          <p>
            Reduce these fractions into lowest terms.
          </p>
        </introduction>
        <task>
          <statement>
            <p>
              <m>\dfrac{14}{42}=</m><var name="$f[0]" width="5" />
            </p>
          </statement>
          <solution>
            <p>
              With <m>\frac{14}{42}</m>, we have <m>\frac{2\cdot7}{2\cdot3\cdot7}</m>, which reduces
              to <m>\frac{1}{3}</m>.
            </p>
          </solution>
        </task>
        <task>
          <statement>
            <p>
              <m>\dfrac{8}{30}=</m><var name="$f[1]" width="5" />
            </p>
          </statement>
          <solution>
            <p>
              With <m>\frac{8}{30}</m>, we have <m>\frac{2\cdot2\cdot2}{2\cdot3\cdot5}</m>, which
              reduces to <m>\frac{4}{15}</m>.
            </p>
          </solution>
        </task>
        <task>
          <statement>
            <p>
              <m>\dfrac{70}{90}=</m><var name="$f[2]" width="5" />
            </p>
          </statement>
          <solution>
            <p>
              With <m>\frac{70}{90}</m>, we have <m>\frac{7\cdot10}{9\cdot10}</m>, which reduces to
              <m>\frac{7}{9}</m>.
            </p>
          </solution>
        </task>
      </webwork>
    </exercise>

    <p>
      Sometimes it is useful to do the opposite of reducing a fraction, and <term>build up</term>
      the fraction to use larger numbers.
    </p>

    <exercise>
      <title>Building Up a Fraction</title>
      <webwork>
        <pg-code>
          Context("Form");
          $p = Formula("84/100");
        </pg-code>
        <statement>
          <p>
            Sayid scored <m>\frac{21}{25}</m> on a recent exam. Build up this fraction so that the
            denominator is <m>100</m>, so that Sayid can understand what percent score he earned.
          </p>
          <p>
            <var name="$p" width="10" />
          </p>
        </statement>
        <solution>
          <p>
            To change the denominator from <m>25</m> to <m>100</m>, it needs to be multiplied by
            <m>4</m>. And then we are obligated to also multiply the nuemrator by <m>4</m>. So we
            have:
            <md>
              <mrow>\frac{21}{25}\amp=\frac{21\cdot4}{25\cdot4}</mrow>
              <mrow>\amp=\frac{84}{100}</mrow>
            </md>
          </p>
          <p>
            And the fraction <m>\frac{21}{25}</m> is equivalent to <m>\frac{84}{100}</m>. (This
            means Sayid scored an <m>84\%</m>.)
          </p>
        </solution>
      </webwork>
    </exercise>
  </subsection>

  <subsection>
    <title>Multiplying with Fractions</title>
    <!-- <example>
      <p>
        Suppose a recipe calls for <m>\frac{2}{3}</m> cup of milk, but we'd like to quadruple the
        recipe (make it four times as big). We'll need four times as much milk, and one way to
        measure this out is to fill a measuring cup to <m>\frac{2}{3}</m> full, four times:
      </p>
      <image>
        <shortdescription>four measuring cups, each filled two-thirds with liquid</shortdescription>
        <latex-image label="measuring-cups">
          \begin{tikzpicture}
            \foreach \x in {0,4,8,12} {
              \fill[color=secondcolor!20] (\x,0) rectangle (2+\x,2.157);
              \draw (\x,0) rectangle (2+\x,3.236);
              \draw (\x,1.079) &#45;- (2+\x,1.079);
              \draw (\x,2.157) &#45;- (2+\x,2.157);
              \draw (\x,3.236) &#45;- (\x-0.5,3.236) &#45;- (\x,2.5);
              \draw (2+\x,3.236) &#45;-+ (1,0) &#45;-+ (1.5,-2) &#45;-+ (1.3,-2.2) &#45;-+ (0.8,-0.2) &#45;-+ (0,-0.2);
            }
          \end{tikzpicture}
        </latex-image>
      </image>
      <p>
        When you count up the shaded thirds, there are eight of them. So multiplying
        <m>\frac{2}{3}</m> by the whole number <m>4</m>, the result is <m>\frac{8}{3}</m>.
        Mathematically:
        <md>
          <mrow>4\cdot\frac{2}{3}\amp=\frac{4\cdot2}{3}</mrow>
          <mrow>\amp=\frac{8}{3}</mrow>
        </md>
      </p>
    </example> -->

    <fact>
      <title>Multiplying a Fraction and a Whole Number</title>
      <p>
        When you multiply a whole number by a fraction, you may just multiply the whole number by
        the numerator and leave the denominator alone. In other words, a whole number and a fraction
        multiply this way:
        <md>
          a \cdot \frac{c}{d} = \frac{a\cdot c}{d}
        </md>
      </p>
    </fact>

    <exercise>
      <title>Whole Number-Fraction Multiplication</title>
      <webwork>
        <pg-code>
          Context("LimitedFraction")->flags->set(
              allowMixedNumbers => 0,
              reduceConstants => 1,
              showMixedNumbers => 0
          );
          Parser::Number::NoDecimals;
          @f=(
            Fraction(10, 9)->cmp(studentsMustReduceFractions => 1),
            Fraction(28, 1)->cmp(studentsMustReduceFractions => 1),
            Fraction(35, 3)->cmp(studentsMustReduceFractions => 1)
          );
        </pg-code>
        <introduction>
          <p>
            Simplify these whole number and fraction products.
          </p>
        </introduction>
        <task>
          <statement>
            <p>
              <m>5\cdot\dfrac{2}{9}=</m><var name="$f[0]" width="10" />
            </p>
          </statement>
          <solution>
            <p>
              Multiplying the <m>5</m> with the numerator <m>2</m> gives a new numerator <m>10</m>.
              We keep the denominator <m>9</m> and the answer is <m>\frac{10}{9}</m>.
            </p>
          </solution>
        </task>
        <task>
          <statement>
            <p>
              <m>12\left(\dfrac{7}{3}\right)=</m><var name="$f[1]" width="10" />
            </p>
          </statement>
          <solution>
            <p>
              Before we multiply, we can do some simplfication first. We want to make
              <m>\frac{12\cdot7}{3}</m>, but now we can cancel a factor of <m>3</m>. We have,
              <m>\frac{\cancelto{12}{4}\cdot7}{\cancelto{3}{1}}</m>. So we have <m>\frac{28}{1}</m>,
              or just <m>28</m>.
            </p>
          </solution>
        </task>
        <task>
          <statement>
            <p>
              <m>14\cdot\dfrac{5}{6}=</m><var name="$f[2]" width="10" />
            </p>
          </statement>
          <solution>
             <p>
              Before we multiply, we can do some simplfication first. We want to make
              <m>\frac{14\cdot5}{6}</m>, but now we can cancel a factor of <m>2</m>. We have,
              <m>\frac{\cancelto{14}{7}\cdot5}{\cancelto{6}{3}}</m>. So we have <m>\frac{35}{3}</m>.
            </p>
         </solution>
        </task>
      </webwork>
    </exercise>

    <!-- <example>
      <p>
        We could also use multiplication to decrease amounts. Suppose we needed to cut the recipe
        down to one fifth of its original size. We only need <em>one fifth</em> of the
        <m>\frac{2}{3}</m> cup milk. So we multiply by <m>\frac{1}{5}</m>. But how much is
        <m>\frac{1}{5}</m> of <m>\frac{2}{3}</m> cup?
      </p>

      <sidebyside widths="77% 16%" margins="0%">
        <p>
          If we cut the measuring cup into five equal vertical strips along with the three equal
          horizontal strips, then in total there are <m>3\cdot5=15</m> subdivisions of the cup. Two
          of those sections represent <m>\frac{1}{5}</m> of the <m>\frac{2}{3}</m> cup.
        </p>
        <image>
          <shortdescription>
            a measuring cup divided evenly into three horizontal sections, but also evenly into five
            vertical sections; in total, there are fifteen sections; the two that correspond to the
            lower two-thirds and leftmost one-fifth are shaded
          </shortdescription>
          <latex-image label="more-measuring-cups">
            \begin{tikzpicture}
              \fill[color=secondcolor!20] (0,0) rectangle (0.4,2.157);
              \fill[color=secondcolor!05] (0.40,0) rectangle (2,2.157);
              \draw (0,0) rectangle (2,3.236);
              \draw (0,1.079) &#45;- (2,1.079);
              \draw (0,2.157) &#45;- (2,2.157);
              \draw (0,3.236) &#45;- (-0.5,3.236) &#45;- (0,2.5);
              \draw (2,3.236) &#45;-+ (1,0) &#45;-+ (1.5,-2) &#45;-+ (1.3,-2.2) &#45;-+ (0.8,-0.2) &#45;-+ (0,-0.2);
              \foreach \x in {0.4,0.8,1.2,1.6} \draw[dashed] (\x,0) &#45;- (\x,3.236);
            \end{tikzpicture}
          </latex-image>
        </image>
      </sidebyside>

      <sidebyside widths="65% 29%" margins="0%">
        <p>
          In the end, we have <m>\frac{2}{15}</m> of a cup. The denominator <m>15</m> came from
          multiplying <m>5</m> and <m>3</m>, the denominators of the fractions we had to multiply.
          The numerator <m>2</m> came from multiplying <m>1</m> and <m>2</m>, the numerators of the
          fractions we had to multiply.
        </p>
        <p>
          <md>
            <mrow>\frac{1}{5}\cdot\frac{2}{3}\amp=\frac{1\cdot2}{5\cdot3}</mrow>
            <mrow>\amp=\frac{2}{15}</mrow>
          </md>
        </p>
      </sidebyside>
    </example> -->

    <fact xml:id="fact-multiplication-of-fractions">
      <title>Multiplication with Fractions</title>                                                            <idx><h>Multiplication</h><h>of fractions</h></idx>
                                                                                                              <idx><h>Fraction</h><h>multiplication</h></idx>
      <statement>
        <p>
          As long as <m>b</m> and <m>d</m> are not <m>0</m>, then fractions multiply this way:
          <md>
            \frac{a}{b} \cdot \frac{c}{d} = \frac{a\cdot c}{b \cdot d}
          </md>
        </p>
      </statement>
    </fact>

    <exercise>
      <title>Fraction Multiplication</title>
      <webwork>
        <pg-code>
          Context("LimitedFraction")->flags->set(
              allowMixedNumbers => 0,
              reduceConstants => 1,
              showMixedNumbers => 0
          );
          Parser::Number::NoDecimals;
          @f=(
            Fraction(10, 21)->cmp(studentsMustReduceFractions => 1),
            Fraction(20, 1)->cmp(studentsMustReduceFractions => 1),
            Fraction(-28, 15)->cmp(studentsMustReduceFractions => 1),
            Fraction(-14, 9)->cmp(studentsMustReduceFractions => 1)
          );
        </pg-code>
        <introduction>
          <p>
            Simplify these fraction products.
          </p>
        </introduction>
        <task>
          <statement>
            <p>
              <m>\dfrac{1}{3}\cdot\dfrac{10}{7}=</m><var name="$f[0]" width="10" />
            </p>
          </statement>
          <solution>
            <p>
              Multiplying numerators gives <m>10</m>, and multiplying denominators gives <m>21</m>.
              The answer is <m>\frac{10}{21}</m>.
            </p>
          </solution>
        </task>
        <task>
          <statement>
            <p>
              <m>\dfrac{12}{3}\cdot\dfrac{15}{3}=</m><var name="$f[1]" width="10" />
            </p>
          </statement>
          <solution>
            <p>
              Before we multiply fractions, note that <m>\frac{12}{3}</m> reduces to <m>4</m>, and
              <m>\frac{15}{3}</m> reduces to <m>5</m>. So we just have <m>4\cdot5=20</m>.
            </p>
          </solution>
        </task>
        <task>
          <statement>
            <p>
              <m>-\dfrac{14}{5}\cdot\dfrac{2}{3}=</m><var name="$f[2]" width="10" />
            </p>
          </statement>
          <solution>
            <p>
              Multiplying numerators gives <m>28</m>, and multiplying denominators gives <m>15</m>.
              The result should be negative, so the answer is <m>-\frac{28}{15}</m>.
            </p>
          </solution>
        </task>
        <task>
          <statement>
            <p>
              <m>\dfrac{70}{27}\cdot\dfrac{12}{-20}=</m><var name="$f[3]" width="10" />
            </p>
          </statement>
          <solution>
            <p>
              Before we multiply fractions, note that <m>\frac{12}{-20}</m> reduces to
              <m>\frac{-3}{5}</m>. So we have <m>\frac{70}{27}\cdot\frac{-3}{5}</m>. Both the
              numerator of the first fraction and denominator of the second fraction are divisible
              by <m>5</m>, so it helps to reduce both fractions accordingly and get
              <m>\frac{14}{27}\cdot\frac{-3}{1}</m>. Both the denominator of the first fraction and
              numerator of the second fraction are divisible by <m>3</m>, so it helps to reduce both
              fractions accordingly and get <m>\frac{14}{9}\cdot\frac{-1}{1}</m>. Now we are just
              multiplying <m>\frac{14}{9}</m> by <m>-1</m>, so the result is <m>\frac{-14}{9}</m>.
            </p>
          </solution>
        </task>
      </webwork>
    </exercise>
  </subsection>

  <subsection>
    <title>Division with Fractions</title>
    <p>
      How does division with fractions work? Are we able to compute/simplify each of these examples?
      <ol marker="a." cols="4">
        <li>
          <p>
            <m>3\div\frac{2}{7}</m>
          </p>
        </li>
        <li>
          <p>
            <m>\frac{18}{19}\div5</m>
          </p>
        </li>
        <li>
          <p>
            <m>\frac{14}{3}\div\frac{8}{9}</m>
          </p>
        </li>
        <li>
          <p>
            <m>\frac{\ \frac{2}{5}\ }{\frac{5}{2}}</m>
          </p>
        </li>
      </ol>
    </p>
    <p>
      We know that dividing something by <m>2</m> is the same as multiplying it by
      <m>\frac{1}{2}</m>. This works in the other direction too: dividing by <m>\frac{1}{2}</m> is
      the same as multiplying by <m>\frac{2}{1}</m>, or just <m>2</m>. The more general property is
      that dividing by <m>\frac{a}{b}</m> is equivalent to multiplying by the reciprocal                      <idx><h>reciprocal</h></idx>
      <m>\frac{b}{a}</m>.
    </p>

    <fact xml:id="fact-division-of-fractions">
      <title>Division with Fractions</title>
      <statement>
        <p>
          As long as <m>b</m>, <m>c</m> and <m>d</m> are not <m>0</m>, then division with fractions
          works this way:
          <md>
            \frac{a}{b} \div \frac{c}{d} = \frac{a}{b}\cdot\frac{d}{c}
          </md>
        </p>
      </statement>
    </fact>

    <example>
      <p>
        With our examples from the beginning of this subsection:
        <ol marker="a." cols="2">
          <li>
            <p>
              <m>\begin{aligned}[t]
              3\div\frac{2}{7}\amp=3\multiplyright{\frac{7}{2}}\\
              \amp=\divideunder{3}{1}\cdot\frac{7}{2}\\
              \amp=\frac{21}{2}\\
              \ 
              \end{aligned}
              </m>
            </p>
          </li>
          <li>
            <p>
              <m>\begin{aligned}[t]
              \frac{18}{19}\div5\amp=\frac{18}{19}\div\divideunder{5}{1}\\
              \amp=\frac{18}{19}\multiplyright{\frac{1}{5}}\\
              \amp=\frac{18}{95}\\
              \ 
              \end{aligned}
              </m>
            </p>
          </li>
          <li>
            <p>
              <m>\begin{aligned}[t]
              \frac{14}{3}\div\frac{8}{9}\amp=\frac{14}{3}\multiplyright{\frac{9}{8}}\\
              \amp=\frac{14}{\highlight{1}}\cdot\frac{\highlight{3}}{8}\\
              \amp=\frac{\highlight{7}}{1}\cdot\frac{3}{\highlight{4}}\\
              \amp=\frac{21}{4}
              \end{aligned}
              </m>
            </p>
          </li>
          <li>
            <p>
              <m>\begin{aligned}[t]
              \frac{\ \frac{2}{5}\ }{\frac{5}{2}}\amp=\frac{2}{5}\highlight{{}\div{}}\frac{5}{2}\\
              \amp=\frac{2}{5}\multiplyright{\frac{2}{5}}\\
              \amp=\frac{4}{25}\\
              \ 
              \end{aligned}
              </m>
            </p>
          </li>
        </ol>
      </p>
    </example>

    <exercise>
      <title>Fraction Division</title>
      <webwork>
        <pg-code>
          Context("LimitedFraction")->flags->set(
              allowMixedNumbers => 0,
              reduceConstants => 1,
              showMixedNumbers => 0
          );
          Parser::Number::NoDecimals;
          @f=(
            Fraction(7, 30)->cmp(studentsMustReduceFractions => 1),
            Fraction(12, 25)->cmp(studentsMustReduceFractions => 1),
            Fraction(-28, 3)->cmp(studentsMustReduceFractions => 1),
            Fraction(-1400, 99)->cmp(studentsMustReduceFractions => 1)
          );
        </pg-code>
        <introduction>
          <p>
            Simplify these fraction division expressions.
          </p>
        </introduction>
        <task>
          <statement>
            <p>
              <m>\dfrac{1}{3}\div\dfrac{10}{7}=</m><var name="$f[0]" width="10" />
            </p>
          </statement>
          <solution>
            <p>
              <m>
              \begin{aligned}[t]
              \frac{1}{3}\div\frac{10}{7}\amp=\frac{1}{3}\cdot\frac{7}{10}\\
              \amp=\frac{7}{30}\\
              \ 
              \end{aligned}
              </m>
            </p>
          </solution>
        </task>
        <task>
          <statement>
            <p>
              <m>\dfrac{12}{5}\div5=</m><var name="$f[1]" width="10" />
            </p>
          </statement>
          <solution>
            <p>
              <m>
              \begin{aligned}[t]
              \frac{12}{5}\div5\amp=\frac{12}{5}\cdot\frac{1}{5}\\
              \amp=\frac{12}{25}\\
              \ 
              \end{aligned}
              </m>
            </p>
          </solution>
        </task>
        <task>
          <statement>
            <p>
              <m>-14\div\dfrac{3}{2}=</m><var name="$f[2]" width="10" />
            </p>
          </statement>
          <solution>
            <p>
              <m>
              \begin{aligned}[t]
              -14\div\frac{3}{2}\amp=-14\cdot\frac{2}{3}\\
              \amp=-\frac{14}{1}\cdot\frac{2}{3}\\
              \amp=-\frac{28}{3}
              \end{aligned}
              </m>
            </p>
          </solution>
        </task>
        <task>
          <statement>
            <p>
              <m>\dfrac{70}{9}\div\dfrac{11}{-20}=</m><var name="$f[3]" width="10" />
            </p>
          </statement>
          <solution>
            <p>
              <m>
              \begin{aligned}[t]
              \frac{70}{9}\div\frac{11}{-20}\amp=-\frac{70}{9}\cdot\frac{20}{11}\\
              \amp=-\frac{1400}{99}\\
              \ 
              \end{aligned}
              </m>
            </p>
          </solution>
        </task>
      </webwork>
    </exercise>
  </subsection>

  <subsection>
    <title>Adding and Subtracting Fractions</title>
    <p>
      With whole numbers and integers, addition and subtraction are straightforward. The situation
      is almost as straightforward with fractions <em>if the two fractions have the same
      denominator</em>. Consider
      <md>
        \frac{7}{2} + \frac{3}{2} = 7\text{ halves}+3\text{ halves}
      </md>
      In the same way that <m>7</m> tacos and <m>3</m> tacos make <m>10</m> tacos, we have:
      <md>
        \begin{array}{ccccc}
        7\text{ halves}{}\amp+{}\amp 3\text{ halves}\amp=\amp 10\text{ halves} \\
        \frac{7}{2}{}\amp+{}\amp\frac{3}{2}\amp=\amp\frac{10}{2} \\
        \amp \amp \amp=\amp5 \\
        \end{array}
      </md>
    </p>

    <fact xml:id="fact-add-fractions-with-same-denominator">
      <title>Adding/Subtracting with Fractions Having the Same Denominator</title>                            <idx><h>Addition</h><h>of fractions with the same denominator</h></idx>
                                                                                                              <idx><h>Denominator</h><h>adding and subtracting fractions with the same</h></idx>
                                                                                                              <idx><h>Fraction</h><h>adding and subtracting with the same denominator</h></idx>
      <statement>
        <p>
          To add or subtract two fractions having the same denominator, <em>keep</em> that
          denominator, and add or subtract the numerators.
          <md>
            <mrow>\frac{a}{b}+\frac{c}{b}\amp=\frac{a+c}{b}\amp\frac{a}{b}-\frac{c}{b}\amp=\frac{a-c}{b}</mrow>
          </md>
          If it's possible, useful, or required of you, simplify the result by reducing to lowest
          terms.
        </p>
      </statement>
    </fact>

    <exercise>
      <title>Fraction Addition and Subtraction</title>
      <webwork>
        <pg-code>
          Context("LimitedFraction")->flags->set(
              allowMixedNumbers => 0,
              reduceConstants => 1,
              showMixedNumbers => 0
          );
          Parser::Number::NoDecimals;
          @f=(
            Fraction(11, 3)->cmp(studentsMustReduceFractions => 1),
            Fraction(4, 3)->cmp(studentsMustReduceFractions => 1)
          );
        </pg-code>
        <introduction>
          <p>
            Add or subtract these fractions.
          </p>
        </introduction>
        <task>
          <statement>
            <p>
              <m>\dfrac{1}{3}+\dfrac{10}{3}=</m><var name="$f[0]" width="10" />
            </p>
          </statement>
          <solution>
            <p>
              Since the denominators are both <m>3</m>,  we can add the numerators: <m>1+10=11</m>.
              The answer is <m>\frac{11}{3}</m>.
            </p>
         </solution>
        </task>
        <task>
          <statement>
            <p>
              <m>\dfrac{13}{6}-\dfrac{5}{6}=</m><var name="$f[1]" width="10" />
            </p>
          </statement>
          <solution>
            <p>
              Since the denominators are both <m>6</m>, we can subtract the numerators:
              <m>13-5=8</m>. The answer is <m>\frac{8}{6}</m>, but that reduces to
              <m>\frac{4}{3}</m>.
            </p>
          </solution>
        </task>
      </webwork>
    </exercise>

    <p>
      But what if the denomiators are not the same? Whenever we'd like to add or subtract fractions
      with differing denominators, finding sums and differences is more complicated.
    </p>

    <example>
      <title>Quarters and Dimes</title>
      <p>
        Find the sum <m>\frac{3}{4}+\frac{2}{10}</m>. Does this seem intimidating? Consider this:
        <ul>
          <li>
            <p>
              <m>\frac{1}{4}</m> of a dollar is a quarter, and so <m>\frac{3}{4}</m> of a dollar is
              <m>75</m> cents.
            </p>
          </li>
          <li>
            <p>
              <m>\frac{1}{10}</m> of a dollar is a dime, and so <m>\frac{2}{10}</m> of a dollar is
              <m>20</m> cents.
            </p>
          </li>
        </ul>
      </p>
      <p>
        So if you know what to look for, the expression <m>\frac{3}{4}+\frac{2}{10}</m> is like
        adding <m>75</m> cents and <m>20</m> cents, which gives you <m>95</m> cents. As a fraction
        of one dollar, that is <m>\frac{95}{100}</m>. So we can report
        <md>
          \frac{3}{4}+\frac{2}{10}=\frac{95}{100}
        </md>.
        (Although we should probably reduce that last fraction to <m>\frac{19}{20}</m>.)
      </p>
    </example>

    <p>
      This example was not something you can apply to other fraction addition situations, because
      the denominators here worked especially well with money amounts. But there is something we can
      learn here. The fraction <m>\frac{3}{4}</m> was equivalent to <m>\frac{75}{100}</m>, and the
      other fraction <m>\frac{2}{10}</m> was equivalent to <m>\frac{20}{100}</m>. These
      <em>equivalent</em> fractions have the same denominator and are therefore <q>easy</q> to add.
      What we saw happen was:
      <md>
        <mrow>\frac{3}{4}+\frac{2}{10}\amp=\frac{75}{100}+\frac{20}{100}</mrow>
        <mrow>\amp=\frac{95}{100}</mrow>
      </md>
    </p>
    <p>
      This gives us a strategy for adding (or subtracting) fractions.
    </p>

    <fact>
      <title>Adding/Subtracting Fractions with Different Denominators</title>                                 <idx><h>Addition</h><h>of fractions with different denominators</h></idx>
                                                                                                              <idx><h>Denominator</h><h>adding and subtracting fractions with different</h></idx>
                                                                                                              <idx><h>Fraction</h><h>adding and subtracting with the different denominators</h></idx>
      <statement>
        <p>
          To add (or subtract) generic fractions together, use their denominators to find a
          <term>common denominator</term>. This means some whole number that is a whole multiple of           <idx><h>Fraction</h><h>common denominator</h></idx>
          both of the original denominators. Then rewrite the two fractions as <em>equivalent</em>            <idx><h>Common denominator</h></idx>
          fractions that use this common denominator. Write the result <em>keeping</em> that                  <idx><h>Denominator</h><h>common</h></idx>
          denominator and adding (or subtracting) the numerators. Reduce the fraction if that is
          useful or required.
        </p>
        <p>
          Among all possible common denominators for two fractions, one option will be smaller than           <idx><h>Denominator</h><h>least common</h></idx>
          all others. This is called the <term>least common denominator</term>.                               <idx><h>Least common denominator (LCD)</h></idx>
        </p>
      </statement>
    </fact>

    <example>
      <p>
        Let's add <m>\frac{2}{3}+\frac{2}{5}</m>. The denominators are <m>3</m> and <m>5</m>, so the
        number <m>15</m> would be a good common denominator.
        <md>
          <mrow>\frac{2}{3}+\frac{2}{5}\amp=\frac{2\multiplyright{5}}{3\multiplyright{5}}+\frac{2\multiplyright{3}}{5\multiplyright{3}}</mrow>
          <mrow>\amp=\frac{10}{15}+\frac{6}{15}</mrow>
          <mrow>\amp=\frac{16}{15}</mrow>
        </md>
      </p>
    </example>

    <exercise>
      <title>Using up the flour</title>
      <webwork>
        <pg-macros>
          <macro-file>contextUnits.pl</macro-file>
        </pg-macros>
        <pg-code>
          Context(context::Units::extending("LimitedFraction")->withUnitsFor("volume"));
          Context()->flags->set(
              allowMixedNumbers => 0,
              reduceConstants => 1,
              showMixedNumbers => 0
          );
          Parser::Number::NoDecimals;
          $flour = Compute('13/24 cup');
        </pg-code>
        <statement>
          <p>
            A chef had <m>\frac{2}{3}</m> cups of flour and needed to use <m>\frac{1}{8}</m> cup to
            thicken a sauce. How much flour is left? <var name="$flour" evaluator="$ev" width="15"/>
          </p>
        </statement>
        <solution>
          <p>
            We need to compute <m>\frac{2}{3} - \frac{1}{8}</m>. The denominators are <m>3</m> and
            <m>8</m>. One common denominator is <m>24</m>, so we move to rewrite each fraction using
            <m>24</m> as the denominator:
            <md>
              <mrow>\frac{2}{3} - \frac{1}{8}\amp=\frac{2\cdot8}{3\cdot8} - \frac{1\cdot3}{8\cdot3}</mrow>
              <mrow>\amp=\frac{16}{24}-\frac{3}{24}</mrow>
              <mrow>\amp=\frac{13}{24}</mrow>
            </md>
          </p>
          <p>
            The numerical result is <m>\frac{13}{24}</m>, but a pure number does not answer this
            question. The amount of flour remaining is <m>\frac{13}{24}</m> <em>cups</em>.
          </p>
        </solution>
      </webwork>
    </exercise>
  </subsection>

  <subsection>
    <title>Mixed Numbers and Improper Fractions</title>
    <p>
      A simple recipe for bread contains only a few ingredients:
    </p>
    <tabular>
      <row>
        <cell><m>1\,\sfrac{1}{2}</m></cell>
        <cell>tablespoons yeast</cell>
      </row>
      <row>
        <cell><m>1\,\sfrac{1}{2}</m></cell>
        <cell>tablespoons kosher salt</cell>
      </row>
      <row>
        <cell><m>6\,\sfrac{1}{2}</m></cell>
        <cell>cups unbleached, all-purpose flour (more for dusting)</cell>
      </row>
    </tabular>
    <p>
      Each ingredient is listed as a <term>mixed number</term> that quickly communicates how many             <idx><h>Fraction</h><h>mixed number</h></idx>
      whole amounts and how many parts are needed. It's useful for quickly communicating a practical          <idx><h>Mixed numbers</h></idx>
      amount of something you are cooking with, measuring on a ruler, purchasing at the grocery
      store, etc. But it causes trouble in an algebra class. The number <m>1\,\sfrac{1}{2}</m> means
      <q>one <alert>and</alert> one half</q>. So really,
      <md>
        1\,\frac{1}{2}=1+\frac{1}{2}
      </md>
      The trouble is that with <m>1\,\sfrac{1}{2}</m>, you have two numbers written right next to
      each other. Normally with two math expressions written right next to each other, they should
      be <em>multiplied</em>, not <em>added</em>. But with a mixed number, they <em>should</em> be
      added.
    </p>
    <sidebyside widths="65% 29%" margins="0%">
      <p>
        Fortunately we just reviewed how to add fractions. If we need to do any arithmetic with a
        mixed number like <m>1\,\sfrac{1}{2}</m>, we can treat it as <m>1+\frac{1}{2}</m> and
        simplify to get a <q>nice</q> fraction instead: <m>\frac{3}{2}</m>. A fraction like
        <m>\frac{3}{2}</m> is called an <term>improper fraction</term> because it's actually larger           <idx><h>Fraction</h><h>improper</h></idx>
        than <m>1</m>. And a <q>proper</q> fraction would be something small that is only                     <idx><h>Improper fraction</h></idx>
        <em>part</em> of a whole instead of <em>more</em> than a whole.
      </p>
      <p>
        <md>
          <mrow>1\,\frac{1}{2}\amp=1+\frac{1}{2}</mrow>
          <mrow>\amp=\frac{1}{1}+\frac{1}{2}</mrow>
          <mrow>\amp=\frac{2}{2}+\frac{1}{2}</mrow>
          <mrow>\amp=\frac{3}{2}</mrow>
        </md>
      </p>
    </sidebyside>
  </subsection>

  <exercises>
    <subexercises>
      <title>Skills Practice</title>
      <exercise label="place-fraction-on-numberline-5-mod-4">
        <webwork>
          <pg-macros>
            <macro-file>parserGraphTool.pl</macro-file>
          </pg-macros>
          <pg-code>
            Context("Fraction");
            $a = Fraction(random(5, 13, 4), 4);
            $numberline = GraphTool("{point, ($a, 0)}")->with(
                numberLine          => 1,
                bBox                => [ -1, 0.4, 4, -0.4 ],
                availableTools      => [ 'PointTool' ],
                snapSizeX           => 1/4,
                ticksDistanceX      => 1,
                minorTicksX         => 3,
                showCoordinateHints => 0
            );
          </pg-code>
          <statement>
            <p>
              Find the fraction <m><var name="$a"/></m> on the numberline.
            </p>
            <p>
              <var name="$numberline" width="1"/>
            </p>
          </statement>
        </webwork>
      </exercise>

